{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8f575e47-b71e-4d70-9512-d836b60d1a08","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, so here's the answer from general knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check Apple's built-in crash reports:**\n   macOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps via `ulimit`:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Core files are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Ensure `/cores` is writable:**\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Check SIP isn't blocking core dumps:**\n   On modern macOS, System Integrity Protection can prevent core dumps for some processes. You may need to codesign your binary with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement:\n   ```bash\n   codesign -s - --entitlements entitlements.plist ./your-app\n   ```\n   where `entitlements.plist` includes `com.apple.security.get-task-allow = true`.\n\n5. **Analyze the dump with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./your-app\n   ```\n\n**Key point for NativeAOT:** Since `createdump` is a CoreCLR utility not shipped with NativeAOT, you must rely on the OS-level core dump mechanism (`/cores/`) or Apple's Crash Reporter as described above.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"15263c34-7c8c-4e5d-93a7-045b06564c28","outputTokens":413,"requestId":"7641:6ABDE:1A7CCED:1E0E328:69FE92AD"},"id":"8daef26b-7c34-434c-a4cf-28d2956a9eb4","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:49:42.899Z","parentId":"ad5b2c56-daaa-4a52-94dd-1e6844dde2be"}
